<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
External morphological characters are concordant with the description of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. maculatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="maculatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3646.4.4" author="Kahn, AS" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="386 - 400" refId="B50" refString="Kahn, AS, Geller, JB, Reiswig, HM, Smith, KL, 2013. Bathydorus laniger and Docosaccus maculatus (Lyssacinosida; Hexactinellida): Two new species of glass sponge from the abyssal eastern North Pacific Ocean. Zootaxa 3646 (4): 386 - 400, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3646.4.4" title="Bathydorus laniger and Docosaccus maculatus (Lyssacinosida; Hexactinellida): Two new species of glass sponge from the abyssal eastern North Pacific Ocean." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3646.4.4" volume="3646" year="2013">Kahn et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). However, sequences for the 16S and COI genes from the holotype are 2.4% and 3.9% divergent (K2P distance), respectively, from the western CCZ specimen. Sequences from 18S and 28S do not match to sequences from 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. maculatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="maculatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The species was described from Station M, off California, in the Pacific Ocean at depths of 3,953-4,000 m, but the genus was originally thought to be restricted to Antarctica (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3646.4.4" author="Kahn, AS" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="386 - 400" refId="B50" refString="Kahn, AS, Geller, JB, Reiswig, HM, Smith, KL, 2013. Bathydorus laniger and Docosaccus maculatus (Lyssacinosida; Hexactinellida): Two new species of glass sponge from the abyssal eastern North Pacific Ocean. Zootaxa 3646 (4): 386 - 400, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3646.4.4" title="Bathydorus laniger and Docosaccus maculatus (Lyssacinosida; Hexactinellida): Two new species of glass sponge from the abyssal eastern North Pacific Ocean." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3646.4.4" volume="3646" year="2013">Kahn et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). This species has been recorded in the CCZ, in the eastern IFREMER contract area and in APEI 3, from 4905-4998 m depth (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-018-0880-y" author="Kersken, D" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="947 - 987" refId="B55" refString="Kersken, D, Janussen, D, Arbizu, PM, 2019. Deep-sea glass sponges (Hexactinellida) from polymetallic nodule fields in the Clarion-Clipperton Fracture Zone (CCFZ), northeastern Pacific: Part II- Hexasterophora. Marine Biodiversity 49 (2): 947 - 987, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-018-0880-y" title="Deep-sea glass sponges (Hexactinellida) from polymetallic nodule fields in the Clarion-Clipperton Fracture Zone (CCFZ), northeastern Pacific: Part II- Hexasterophora." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-018-0880-y" volume="49" year="2019">Kersken et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen collected in the western CCZ differs from the holotype of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. maculatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="maculatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having more parietal oscula, and is smaller, and therefore considered a different species. External morphological characters also differ from the other species reported for the CCZ, 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. nidulus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nidulus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. nidulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kersken, Janussen &amp; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Martínez">Martinez</normalizedToken>
Arbizu, 2019.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">This specimen was found anchored to abyssal sediments of APEI 7 at 4860 m depth.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparison with image-based catalogue.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A very similar 
<taxonomicName class="Hexactinellida" family="Euplectellidae" genus="Docosaccus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Docosaccus" order="Lyssacinosida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Docosaccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. morphotype (i.e., 
<taxonomicName class="Hexactinellida" family="Euplectellidae" genus="Docosaccus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Docosaccus maculatus" order="Lyssacinosida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="maculatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Docosaccus maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. inc., HEX_015) has been very frequently encountered in seabed image surveys conducted across nodule fields areas of the eastern CCZ and in abyssal areas of the Kiribati EEZ.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
